File structure refers to the organization of data in files on secondary storage (e.g., sequential, indexed). Storage structure refers to the representation of data in main memory (e.g., arrays, linked lists).

To implement a stack using queues:
1. Use two queues (q1 and q2).
2. For push(x): enqueue x into q2, then dequeue all elements from q1 and enqueue into q2. Swap names of q1 and q2.
3. For pop(): dequeue from q1.
4. For top(): front of q1.

Example in C++:
class Stack {
    queue<int> q1, q2;
public:
    void push(int x) {
        q2.push(x);
        while(!q1.empty()) {
            q2.push(q1.front());
            q1.pop();
        }
        swap(q1, q2);
    }
    void pop() { q1.pop(); }
    int top() { return q1.front(); }
};
